<P><B>[December 3-4, 2008]</B> We hosted <a href="http://phytophthora.ucr.edu/default.html" target="_blank">Mike Coffey</a>, <a href="http://www.plantpathology.ucr.edu/" target="_blank">Department of Plant Pathology and Microbiology, University of California, Riverside</a>, to discuss collaborative work on natural variation in <i>Phytophthora</i>. Mike gave an inspiring seminar titled "The Plant Destroyer: A Global Perspective Using Nuclear and Mitochondrial Genome Sequences to Study Diversity in <i>Phytophthora</i>" during which he described the World Phytophthora Collection that he curates.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/MikeCoffey_08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/MikeCoffey_08.jpg" width="180" height="130"></a></P>

<P><B>[November 20, 2008]</B> Estelle Verzaux, a graduate student at the <a href="http://www.plantbreeding.wur.nl/" target="_blank">Plant Breeding Department, Wageningen UR</a>, visited the lab for a collaborative project involving the group of <a href="http://www.tsl.ac.uk/profile/cyril-zipfel.asp" target="_blank">Cyril Zipfel</a>.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/Estelle_08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/Estelle_08.jpg" width="150" height="85"></a></P>

<P><B>[October 29, 2008]</B> Farewell Jorunn! After more than six years, Jorunn Bos is leaving the lab. She will be dearly missed for many reasons including her no-nonsense and professional attitude. Jorunn will not be drifting too far though as she will be joining the lab of <a href="http://www.jic.ac.uk/staff/saskia-hogenhout/default.htm" target="_blank">Saskia Hogenhout</a> at the <a href="http://www.jic.ac.uk/" target="_blank">John Innes Centre</a> to work on aphid-plant interactions. Obviously, Jorunn knows better than US vice presidential candidate Sarah Palin who recently <a href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=Eg1vIeuQT1s" target="_blank">ridiculed research on insects (fruit flies)</a>. Read this interesting <a href="http://sciencenow.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/2008/1028/1" target="_blank">commentary in Science</a> on the topic.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/Jorunn_farewell2.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/Jorunn_farewell1.jpg" width="400" height="130"></a></P>

<P><B>[October 28, 2008]</B> <a href="http://www.aber.ac.uk/biology/dept/jhd.html" target="_blank">John Draper</a>, University of Wales, Aberystwyth, and his graduate student Stuart Snowden visited the lab. John gave a seminar titled "Metabolic re-programming following rice blast infection".</P>

<P><B>[October 16, 2008]</B> We hosted Doil Choi and Sang-Keun Oh, <a href="http://www.useoul.edu/" target="_blank">Seoul National University</a>, Republic of Korea, to discuss collaborative work on <i>Phytophthora capsici</i>. Sang-Keun was a member of the the lab at Ohio State and presented a seminar on his most recent work. Doil gave a seminar describing his group's work on genome sequencing of chromosome 2 of tomato as well as their activities in pepper genomics. <a href="http://www.sgn.cornell.edu/community/feature/200405.pl" target="_blank">Click here</a> to find out more about Doil's previous lab at the Korea Research Institute of Bioscience & Biotechnology.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/Doil.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/Doil.jpg" width="350" height="95"></a></P>

<P><B>[October 15, 2008]</B> Farewell to Miriam who is returning to Pamplona, Spain, after completing her internship.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/Miriam_farewell.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/Miriam_farewell.jpg" width="450" height="120"></a></P>

<P><B>[October 11, 2008]</B> Human evolution stopping? Wrong, wrong, wrong. <a href="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/biology/academic-staff/jones/jones.htm" target="_blank">Steve Jones</a>, University College London, presented a much debated lecture at the recent JIC/TSL Annual Science Meeting. Read this <a href="http://johnhawks.net/weblog/topics/evolution/selection/jones-evolution-stopping-2008.html" target="_blank">convincing point-by-point rebuttal of Steve Jones thesis</a> from a leading evolution blogger.</P>

<P><B>[October 6, 2008]</B> Celebration time! <a href="http://www.tsl.ac.uk/profile/id.asp?id=5777" target="_blank">Sebastian Schornack</a> was awarded a 2-year fellowship from the <a href="http://www.dfg.de/en/" target="_blank">Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (German Research Foundation)</a>. Prost!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/Sebastian_DFG08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/Sebastian_DFG08.jpg" width="450" height="110"></a></P>

<P><B>[October 6, 2008]</B> Sylvain Raffaele, <a href="http://www.biomemb.cnrs.fr" target="_blank">Laboratoire de Biogenese Membranaire, University of Bordeaux, France</a>, joined the lab. He plans to remain glued to the computer for some time.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/Sylvain.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/Sylvain.jpg" width="200" height="145"></a></P>

<P><B>[September 30, 2008]</B> <a href="http://plantpathology.tamu.edu/directory/faculty/dickman.asp" target="_blank">Marty Dickman</a>, Director of the Institute of Plant Genomics and Biotechnology, Texas A&M University, visited the lab and presented a seminar titled 'Death be not Proud: Modulation of Programmed Cell Death for Disease Development/Stress Tolerance in Plants'.</P>

<P><B>[September 25, 2008]</B> We welcome back Angela Chaparro-Garcia! Angela did an internship in the lab back in Ohio and then joined the lab of <a href="http://www.biology.buffalo.edu/dept/faculty/ferkey/ferkey.html" target="_blank">Denise Ferkey, SUNY Buffalo</a>, for 1 year to work on chemosensory behavior in <i>C. elegans</i>. A quick sip of champagne with her mentor Jorunn Bos and then off to the bench!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/Angela.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/Angela.jpg" width="400" height="145"></a></P>

<P><B>[September 15, 2008]</B> Rhys Farrer, who recently finished an MSc in bioinformatics at the <a href="http://www1.uea.ac.uk/cm/Home" target="_blank">University of East Anglia</a> joined the lab to work on comparative genomics of <i>Phytophthora</i> spp. Rhys will be working closely with <a href="http://www.tsl.ac.uk/profile/david-studholme.asp" target="_blank">David Studholme</a> who leads TSL Bioinformatics team.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/rhys08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/rhys08.jpg" width="180" height="120"></a></P>

<P><B>[September 5, 2008]</B> Another <a
href="http://www.new-ag.info/08/05/focuson/focuson1.php"
target="_blank">article on potato late blight in the New
Agriculturist</a>. This time mentioning "blue 13", the emerging clonal
lineage of <i>P. infestans</i> that dominates UK populations.</P>

<P><B>[August 27, 2008]</B> Travel mementoes. The <a href="http://www.icpp2008.org/" target="_blank">International Congress of Plant Pathology</a> in Torino, Italy, was a chance to catch up with friends and colleagues, such as <a href="http://ag.udel.edu/meyers_lab/" target="_blank">Blake Meyers</a> and <a href="http://michelmorelab.ucdavis.edu/" target="_blank">Richard Michelmore</a>. What a surprise when Blake and Sophien appeared dressed up with the exact same shirt! Any resemblance to <a href="http://www.alice-in-wonderland.net/alicepic/disney-movie/ tweedledee-tweedledum-2.jpg" target="_blank">Tweedledum and Tweedledee</a> is purely coincidental.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/Torino_08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/Torino_08.jpg" width="450" height="185"></a></P>

<P><B>[July 26, 2008]</B> Catherine Bruce, along with husband Alan and
15 month-old son MJ, visited this week-end. Catherine obtained her Ph.D.
with <a href="http://www.abdn.ac.uk/ims/staff/details.php?id=p.vanwest"
target="_blank">Pieter van West</a> at the University of Aberdeen. She
then joined the Kamoun Lab at Ohio State before moving on to postdocs on
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Candida_albicans"
target="_blank"><i>Candida albicans</i></a> and <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toxoplasma"
target="_blank"><i>Toxoplasma gondii</i></a> at Newcastle University. <a
href="http://youtube.com/watch?v=FxpPWv-6UVA" target="_blank">Watch
Catherine perform a parody of an Elton John song on YouTube</a>.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/CathB_08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG
SRC="images/CathB_08.jpg" width="450" height="105"></a></P>

<P><B>[July 24-25, 2008]</B> <a
href="http://www.scri.ac.uk/staff/paulbirch" target="_blank">Paul
Birch</a>, Scottish Crop Research Institute and Dundee University,
visited the lab and presented a talk entitled "Manipulation of host defences by
pathogen effectors".</P>

<P><B>[July 21, 2008]</B> A series of news reports describe
<a
href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/planth/pestnote/newram.pdf"
target="_blank"><i>Phytophthora ramorum</i></a> and <a
href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/planth/pestnote/kern.pdf"
target="_blank"><i>Phytophthora kernoviae</i></a> as emerging threats to British trees.
There was the usual irritation of seeing several news outlets, including
<a
href="http://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/spread-of-killer-
fungus-threatens-british-trees-872820.html" target="_blank">The
Independent</a>, <a
href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/main.jhtml?xml=/earth/2008/07/22/
eafungus122.xml" target="_blank">The Telegraph</a>, and <a
href="http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-1037023/Fungus-
disease-wipe-millions-British-shrubs.html" target="_blank">The Daily
Mail</a>, refer to <i>Phytophthora</i> as a "fungus". But the BBC News Channel topped them all with its report on <a
href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/glasgow_and_west/7485250.stm"
target="_blank">"a deadly plant virus"</a>!</P>

<P><B>[July 20, 2008]</B> Did you know that we have a connection with <a
href="http://www.pixar.com/" target="_blank">Pixar Animation
Studios</a>? Allison Styer, who as an undergraduate intern wrote the
first scripts for PexFinder and co-authored Torto et al. (<a
href="pdfs/GR_03.pdf">2003, Genome Res 13:1675</a>), now works at Pixar.
Find Allison in the <a
href="http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/379342/WALL-E/credits"
target="_blank">production credits of Pixar's recent movie
"Wall-E"</a>.</P>

<P><B>[July 9, 2008]</B> Miriam Oses Ruiz, who recently finished her MSc
at Wageningen University working with <a
href="http://www.php.wur.nl/UK/Staff/PermanentStaff/dr.+J.A.L.+van+Kan/"
>Jan van Kan</a>, joined the lab. A quick birthday celebration and then
off to the bench!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/Miriam2_08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG
SRC="images/Miriam1_08.jpg" width="450" height="100"></a></P>

<P><B>[July 8, 2008]</B> Check this <a
href="http://www.new-ag.info/08/04/pov.php" target="_blank">interesting
article in the New Agriculturist</a> on the importance of potato as a
subsistence crop, especially in the context of record high food prices.
2008 is the United Nations International Year of the Potato. <a
href="http://www.potato2008.org/en/index.html" target="_blank">Click here
to find out more.</a></P>

<P><B>[June 1, 2008]</B> Back to the future. We welcome back to the lab
Tolga (aka Osman) Bozkurt (left), Middle East Technical University, Ankara, Turkey, and Ricardo
Oliva (right), Centro International de la Papa (CIP), Quito, Ecuador.
Both Tolga and Ricardo previously spent time in the lab at Ohio
State.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/TolgaRicardo08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG
SRC="images/TolgaRicardo08.jpg" width="350" height="150"></a></P>

<P><B>[May 31-June 3, 2008]</B> Into the wild! Liliana Cano and Saskia
Hogenhout traveled to Colorado as part of the project on fungal mimicry
of flowers (<i>Puccinia monoica</i> on <i>Boechera</i> sp.). A successful
trip despite the snow and a stubborn deer that somehow bumped into the
jeep.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/Colorado08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG
SRC="images/Colorado08.jpg" width="450" height="120"></a></P>

<P><B>[May 9, 2008]</B> We're back from Birnam, Scotland, where the
entire lab attended the Annual Meeting of the <a
href="http://pmgn.vbi.vt.edu/index.php" target="_blank">Oomycete
Molecular Genetics Network (OMGN)</a> (~100 participants this year!).
Great science but also time to catch up with colleagues, friends, and
lab alumni. Many thanks to <a
href="http://www.scri.ac.uk/staff/paulbirch" target="_blank">Paul
Birch</a> and his team at the Scottish Crop Research Institute for a
wonderful meeting. <a href="http://web.mac.com/sophien/Site2/OMGN08.html"
target="_blank">Click here for more photos</a>.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/omgn08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG
SRC="images/omgn08.jpg" width="450" height="110"></a></P>

<P><B>[May 8, 2008]</B> <a href="pdfs/MPMI_08b.pdf">Our collaborative
paper</a> with <a
href="http://labs.plantbio.cornell.edu/rose/people/cynthia.htm"
target="_blank">Cynthia Damasceno</a> and <a
href="http://labs.plantbio.cornell.edu/rose/index.htm"
target="_blank">Joss Rose</a>, Cornell University, on structure and
evolution of <i>Phytophthora</i> glucanase inhibitors was
featured on the <a
href="http://apsjournals.apsnet.org/page/mpmi_cover_6-08"
target="_blank">cover of MPMI</a>. Congratulations Cynthia and Joss!</P>

<P><B>[April 21, 2008]</B> <a
href="http://www.ayeaye.tsl.ac.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view
&id=100&Itemid=238" target="_blank">Cyril Zipfel</a> and Sophien
Kamoun's groups celebrated in style the funding of their proposals by
the <a
href="http://www.bbsrc.ac.uk/funding/grants/plant_microbial/index.html"
target="_blank">BBSRC Plant and Microbial Sciences Committee</a>.
Cheers!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/BBSRC_08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG
SRC="images/BBSRC_08.jpg" width="400" height="110"></a></P>

<P><B>[April 10, 2008]</B> Marc Ghislain and Jan Kreuze, <a
href="http://www.cipotato.org" target="_blank">International Potato
Center CIP</a>, stopped by to discuss potato late blight research.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/CIP_08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG
SRC="images/CIP_08.jpg" width="200" height="130"></a></P>

<P><B>[March-April, 2008]</B> Travel mementoes. (left) Zhu-Pin Lin, graduate student at
the <a href="http://ppme.ez-show.com/in/front/bin/home.phtml"
target="_blank"> Department of Plant Pathology, National Taiwan
University, Taipei</a>, proudly displays her heavily highlighted copy of <a
href="pdfs/PNAS_05.pdf">Armstrong et al. (PNAS, 2005)</a>. Note the use
of 4 different colors! (right) Heavily annotated copy of <a
href="pdfs/PlantPhys_05.pdf">Tian et al. (Plant Physiol, 2005)</a> by
Chunbo Liang, graduate student at the <a
href="http://www.ivfcaas.ac.cn/english/index.asp"
target="_blank">Institute of Vegetables and Flowers, Chinese Academy of
Agricultural Sciences, Beijing</a>.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/annotations08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/annotations08.jpg" width="300"
height="125"></a></P>

<P><B>[March 5, 2008]</B> We hosted Joann
Mudge, <a href="http://www.ncgr.org/" target="_blank">National Center for Genome Resources</a>, Santa Fe, New Mexico, to discuss the <i>P. capsici</i> genome project. Joann presented a seminar titled '<i>Phytophthora capsici</i>: de novo genome assembly incorporating next generation sequencing'. Check the <a href="http://capsici.ncgr.org/" target="_blank">Alpheus <i>P. capsici</i> database</a></P>

<P><B>[February 4, 2008]</B> Sebastian Schornack, Martin-Luther-University Halle-Wittenberg, joined the lab. A
quick birthday celebration and then off to the bench!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/sebastien08.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/sebastien08.jpg" width="300"
height="110"></a></P>

<P><B>[January 31, 2008]</B> <a href="http://www.keele.ac.uk/depts/aep/staff/rde.htm" target="_blank">Richard
Emes</a>, Keele University, visited the lab and presented a seminar titled 'Comparative genomics and
adaptive evolution: being positive about selection'.</P>

<P><B>[December 21, 2007]</B> Mireille van Damme received the <a
href="http://www.leverhulme.ac.uk/grants_awards/grants/Technology_Transfer_Award/" target="_blank">Leverhulme
Trust Technology Transfer Award</a> for her thesis work in the van den Ackerveken lab, Utrecht University, and
just had one of her thesis chapters accepted in Plant Journal. Congrats Mireille!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/mireille07.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/mireille07.jpg" width="300"
height="110"></a></P>

<P><B>[November 19, 2007]</B> <a href="http://www.plantchemetics.org/" target="_blank">Renier van
der Hoorn</a> visited the lab and presented a seminar titled 'Activity-based profiling of
plant-pathogen interactions'.</P> 

<P><B>[November 15, 2007]</B> We hosted <a
href="https://www.uni-hohenheim.de/~spring/index-Dateien/Page620.htm" target="_blank">Marco Thines</a> for discussions on oomycete
evolution and taxonomy. Marco presented a talk "Phylogeny and diversity of
Hyaloperonospora and Hy. arabidopsis cluster- a model system for investigating evolution,
speciation and host-pathogen relationships of obligate parasitc pathogens".</P>

<P><B>[October 31, 2007]</B> Lab opening complete with a ribbon cutting ceremony!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><a href="images/ribbon.jpg" target="_blank"><IMG SRC="images/ribbon.jpg" width="450"
